{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:40:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:40:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15481"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15481"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.22,0.17,0.14,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8172"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70124"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2489"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19795"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with persistent wheeze and breathlessness despite adherence to high-dose inhaled corticosteroids and long-acting beta agonists. Her symptoms have not improved despite multiple increases in her asthma medications. She reports that her symptoms are worse during inspiration and she feels tightness in her throat.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions most commonly mimics asthma symptoms and may explain a poor response to asthma treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allergic rhinosinusitis","Vocal cord dysfunction","Gastroesophageal reflux","Obstructive sleep apnoea","Obesity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVocal cord dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E frequently mimics asthma symptoms and is characterised by paradoxical adduction (closure) of the vocal cords during inspiration, when they should normally abduct (open). This creates upper airway obstruction leading to inspiratory stridor, throat tightness, and dyspnoea. The condition can be triggered by stress, exercise, irritants, or post-nasal drip. Importantly, it shows poor response to bronchodilators and may coexist with asthma in up to 40% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther conditions that can mimic or worsen asthma include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic rhinosinusitis\u003C/strong\u003E - Can worsen asthma control through increased mouth breathing and postnasal drip\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroesophageal reflux\u003C/strong\u003E - May trigger bronchospasm and cough\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive sleep apnoea\u003C/strong\u003E - Can cause nocturnal symptoms that may be confused with nighttime asthma\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E - Can cause breathlessness and wheeze through mechanical effects on the chest wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of vocal cord dysfunction typically requires laryngoscopy during symptoms, which reveals paradoxical vocal cord movement. Treatment focuses on speech therapy, breathing exercises, and addressing underlying triggers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Vocal cord dysfunction involves paradoxical adduction (closure) of the vocal cords during inspiration instead of normal abduction (opening).","Key features distinguishing vocal cord dysfunction from asthma include inspiratory stridor, throat tightness, and poor response to bronchodilators.","Vocal cord dysfunction can be triggered by stress, exercise, irritants, or post-nasal drip and may coexist with asthma in up to 40% of cases."],"references":["Benninger C, Parsons JP, Mastronarde JG. Vocal cord dysfunction and asthma. Curr Opin Pulm Med. 2011 Jan;17(1):45-9. doi: 10.1097/MCP.0b013e32834130ee. PMID: 21330824.","Boulet LP, Boulay M\u00c8. Asthma-related comorbidities. Expert Rev Respir Med. 2011 Jun;5(3):377-93. doi: 10.1586/ers.11.34. PMID: 21702660.","Balkissoon R, Kenn K. Asthma: vocal cord dysfunction (VCD) and other dysfunctional breathing disorders. Semin Respir Crit Care Med. 2012 Dec;33(6):595-605. doi: 10.1055/s-0032-1326959. Epub 2012 Oct 9. PMID: 23047311.","Cazzola M, Rogliani P, Ora J, Calzetta L, Matera MG. Asthma and comorbidities: recent advances. Pol Arch Intern Med. 2022 Apr 28;132(4):16250. doi: 10.20452/pamw.16250. Epub 2022 Apr 28. PMID: 35485651.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70124"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15481"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70124"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-17T23:15:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-17T23:16:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8172"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags",